Tony Blair said that he would use the opportunity to return as a British prime minister - but concedes that a comeback is unlikely.
In an interview this evening to mark the fifth anniversary of his retirement from the office of the 59-year-old announced his views on various domestic issues.
Since his resignation in June 2007 after a decade as head of Blair has largely avoided to comment on British politics, and mostly confined his comments to the foreign policy and its role as an envoy of the Quartet of peacemakers in the Middle East.
Asked whether he would like to return to the post of prime minister, Blair was quoted by the Evening Standard in London, with the words: "Yes, sure, but it is unlikely that this happens, so..."
